review.body:
**Actionable comments posted: 2**
🧹 Nitpick comments (5)
components/board/SortButton.tsx (1)
`44-74`: **Strengthen typing of onValueChange to eliminate stringly-typed parsing** You can prevent malformed values at compile time by using a template-literal union. This reduces the need for runtime validation and parsing errors. Apply this diff to tighten the type: ```diff function getSortKey( criterion: SortCriterion, direction?: SortDirection ): string { if (criterion === "none") return "none"; return `${criterion}@${direction || "desc"}`; } +type SortValue = "none" | `${SortCriterion}@${SortDirection}`; + -export default function SortButton({ className }: Readonly) { +export default function SortButton({ className }: Readonly) { const [currentSort, setCurrentSort] = useState({ criterion: "none", }); - const handleSortChange = (value: string) => { + const handleSortChange = (value: SortValue) => { let sortOption: SortOption; if (value === "none") { sortOption = { criterion: "none" }; } else { const parts = value.split("@"); if (parts.length !== 2) { console.error(`Invalid sort value format: ${value}`); return; } const [criterionStr, directionStr] = parts; const validCriteria: SortCriterion[] = ["creation-time", "vote-count"]; const validDirections: SortDirection[] = ["asc", "desc"]; ```
components/common/MarkdownRender.tsx (3)
`31-41`: **Add missing table mappings for tfoot and caption** Your UI suite provides TableFooter and TableCaption but they aren’t wired here, so Markdown tfoot/caption won’t render via the styled components. Apply this diff to import and map them: ```diff import { Table, TableBody, TableCell, TableHead, TableHeader, + TableFooter, + TableCaption, TableRow, } from "@/components/ui/table"; @@ const markdownComponents = { a: MarkdownAnchor, hr: Separator, table: Table, tbody: TableBody, thead: TableHeader, + tfoot: TableFooter, th: TableHead, td: TableCell, tr: TableRow, + caption: TableCaption, }; ``` --- `51-55`: **Hoist plugin arrays and consider extending sanitize schema to explicitly allow GFM tables** Creating new arrays on each render is minor, but easy to avoid. Also, depending on rehype-sanitize’s defaultSchema can be brittle for GFM tables/alignment. Consider explicitly adding table-related tags to the schema to future-proof. Apply this diff to use hoisted plugin arrays: ```diff - + ``` Add the following near the components map to hoist and (optionally) extend schema: ```typescript // Hoisted plugins and a schema that explicitly allows table tags. // Keep/remove the schema extension depending on your threat model. const sanitizeSchema = { ...defaultSchema, tagNames: [ ...(defaultSchema.tagNames ?? []), "table", "thead", "tbody", "tfoot", "tr", "th", "td", "caption", ], } as const; const remarkPlugins = [remarkGfm, remarkBreaks] as const; const rehypePlugins = [[rehypeSanitize, { schema: sanitizeSchema }]] as const; ``` --- `47-59`: **Public API JSDoc for MarkdownRender** Add a short JSDoc so consumers know behavior (GFM enabled, sanitized, custom link/table renderers). Apply this diff: ```diff -interface MarkdownRenderProps { +/** + * Renders Markdown content with: + * - GFM (tables, strikethrough, task lists) and soft-breaks + * - Sanitization via rehype-sanitize + * - Custom renderers for links (CustomLink), hr (Separator), and tables (UI table suite) + */ +interface MarkdownRenderProps { content: string; } -const MarkdownRender = memo(function MarkdownRender({ +const MarkdownRender = memo(function MarkdownRender({ content, }: Readonly) { ```
components/ui/table.tsx (1)
`1-121`: **Optional: JSDoc for public UI primitives** Consider brief JSDoc for the table primitives (Table, TableHeader, etc.) to document styling conventions and usage (e.g., scrolling wrapper on Table). I can add concise JSDoc blocks if you want them included in this PR.

issue.title: chore(deps): bump react-pdf from 9.2.1 to 10.1.0
issue.body:
Bumps [react-pdf](https://github.com/wojtekmaj/react-pdf/tree/HEAD/packages/react-pdf) from 9.2.1 to 10.1.0.
Release notes

Sourced from react-pdf's releases.

v10.1.0

What's new?

  • Added support for functions as children. React-PDF has never been simpler to work with! Say goodbye toonLoadSuccess, say goodbye to setting number of pages in your own state, say goodbye to extra renders! Now, rendering a simple document is as trivial as: 
    <Document file="sample.pdf">
  {({ pdf }) => Array(pdf.numPages)
    .fill(null)
    .map((_, index) => <Page key={index} pageIndex={index} />
  ))}
</Document>
    Thanks @​adamaoc for inspiration!
  • Updated PDF.js to 5.3.93.
  • Updated documentation on JPEG 2000 support.
  • Updated dependencies.
  • Exported LinkService type for convenience.

What's changed?

  • usePageContext will now provide non-null value sooner than before, before the page is actually loaded. This is uniform with how useDocumentContext behaves and with how types were designed from the start, so you should not be affected by this change.
  • React-PDF now targets es2018 and not es2017. PDF.js, our core dependency, already used modern JavaScript syntax, so you should not be affected by this change.

v10.0.1

Bug fixes

  • Fixed commonly used types not reexported.

v10.0.0

See Upgrade guide from version 9.x to 10.x.

After more than a year since our last major release, we're thrilled to bring you React-PDF 10.

This update includes a major PDF.js upgrade, new features to make your life easier, improved stability, and some important breaking changes.

👀 Want to see exciting features more often? Consider sponsoring React-PDF.

❗️ = breaking change

What's new?

  • ❗️ Dropped CommonJS build, making the package ESM-only. Chances are you're not going to be affected by this change at all, as all common bundlers support ESM out of the box.
    • However, you may encounter issues running unit tests using Jest. Consider migrating to Vitest.
  • Updated PDF.js to 5.3.31.
    • Performance boosts: Key rendering routines refactored to cut memory usage and speed up page loading.
    • JPEG2000 downscaling: Automatic downscale of large JPEG2000 images during decoding to improve render times.
    • CMYK JPEG fix: Correct handling of the alpha channel when WebAssembly is disabled.
    • Viewer stability: Better handling of missing/invalid Content-Range headers.
    • API cleanup: Removed deprecated options, adopted parameter objects for core methods, and introduced private class fields for cleaner code.
  • Added support for scale prop in Document component, allowing you to set the scale for the entire document.

... (truncated)

  • 811614c Add support for render props in Document and Page components

  • f4aeddc Target es2018, not es2015/es2017

  • 319c23f Add type declaration

issue.title: Advice on collectstatic in build stage
issue.body:
So I'd be glad to have your help here with an issue but maybe also something to reconsider for this project.

Basically I'm deploying to Railway which injects ENV vars in the build stage of the Dockerfile only if they're specified as `ARG`.

I have an app that requires ENV vars that shouldn't have a default value (for example: fail loudly if we don't have `EMAIL_TOKEN`). Those are defined in my settings module.

You can see where I'm going with this. If I want to use this template on Railway I have two choices:

1. Move `collectstatic` out of the Dockerfile (will this have negative consequences? What do I do in development mode?)

2. Always define defaults for ENV vars. Passing each required ENV var as ARG to Dockerfile is not realistic, there are too many. Even if I was willing to pass secrets as ARGs (and I'm not)

Can collectstatic be moved out of Dockerfile somehow, without negative consequences?

comment.body:
> Another thing I'm considering is just moving this block out of build time and to runtime (since I'm already doing this in Railway anyway).

Just to close the loop on this, this is what I ended up doing. My project is quite complex, old (8 years old), and I wouldn't like to introduce conditional logic for my environment variables. I'm using healthchecks to verify the new deployments have finished doing maintenance (`migrate` and `collectstatic`) where possible. Thanks for all the help @nickjj!

pull_request.title:
[WIP] Role: Senior Python architect.
Repo: https://github.com/DolceVitaUkr/Trading-bot-Python
Goal: Audit and refactor so all modules interconnect correctly with zero dead ends, no duplicate data sources, and one centralized configuration + data registry for...
pull_request.body:
Thanks for asking me to work on this. I will get started on it and keep this PR's description up to date as I form a plan and make progress.

Original description:

> Role: Senior Python architect.
> Repo: https://github.com/DolceVitaUkr/Trading-bot-Python
> Goal: Audit and refactor so all modules interconnect correctly with zero dead ends, no duplicate data sources, and one centralized configuration + data registry for Crypto, Forex, and Forex Options (training now, live later). Preserve my naming style (e.g., Train_RL_Model, Save_AI_Update, Fetch_Symbol, etc.).
> 
> 1) Inventory & Map (Auto-generate)
> 
> Build an inventory of packages, modules, and entry points:
> 
> Produce artifacts/module_map.json with: {module, imports, file, used_by, last_modified}.
> 
> Produce artifacts/dependency_graph.png (static import graph).
> 
> Flag problems:
> 
> Orphans (no one imports them), leaf executables (scripts w/o callers), duplicate modules (same purpose, diff names), multiple mains, cyclic deps.
> 
> Hard-coded paths, duplicate config constants, print() logging, direct file I/O bypassing data layer.
> 
> 2) Central Config & Data Registry (Single Source of Truth)
> 
> Ensure one canonical config.py and one Data_Registry.py:
> 
> config.py: modes, paths, API keys via env, rate limits, feature flags (paper/live), branch list.
> 
> Data_Registry.py: returns canonical paths for datasets, models, logs, metrics:
> 
> data/metrics/{branch}/{mode}/...
> 
> data/decisions/{branch}/{mode}/...
> 
> backup_data/historical/{exchange}/{symbol}/...
> 
> models/{branch}/...
> 
> Replace all scattered paths & magic strings with Data Registry calls.
> 
> Output a diff list of all replaced imports/paths → artifacts/path_replacements.md.
> 
> 3) Interface Contracts (ABC) & Adapters
> 
> Create/confirm interfaces (abstract base classes) with clear method signatures:
> 
> interfaces/MarketData.py → subscribe_bars(), get_history(), close()
> 
> interfaces/Execution.py → place_order(), cancel(), get_positions()
> 
> interfaces/WalletSync.py → balances(), pnl()
> 
> interfaces/NewsFeed.py → latest_headlines(), sentiment()
> 
> interfaces/ValidationRunner.py → backtest(), walk_forward(), approve()
> 
> Ensure each branch uses these interfaces only (no broker-specific calls in strategy/training code).
> 
> Output conformance report → artifacts/interface_conformance.md showing which module implements which interface and any missing methods.
> 
> 4) Kill “Dead Ends” & Duplicates
> 
> Detect and either remove or merge:
> 
> Duplicate indicator/strategy/train modules with overlapping names or logic.
> 
> Unreachable code paths (never imported/run).
> 
> Legacy loggers not using the central logger.
> 
> Produce artifacts/deprecations.md with: file, rationale, action (removed / merged / kept).
> 
> 5) Unified Logging, Telemetry, and Errors
> 
> Ensure one Log_Manager with structured JSON logs (timestamp, branch, mode, component, event, message, extras).
> 
> Replace print() with logger calls everywhere (automate where safe).
> 
> Add Error_Log with branch-scoped rotating files and a central index.
> 
> Emit Telemetry events to a single bus (in-proc now) so UI can subscribe.
> 
> 6) Data Compatibility & Schema Checks
> 
> Verify bar schemas (timestamp TZ, OHLCV, timeframe), indicator columns, and options greeks schema are consistent.
> 
> Add schema validators that run on load and fail fast with actionable error messages.
> 
> Produce artifacts/schema_report.md (per dataset & branch) + auto-fix suggestions.
> 
> 7) Mode & Branch Guards
> 
> Enforce per-branch mode ∈ {paper, live} at Execution layer.
> 
> Disallow any fund transfers (guard raises).
> 
> Ensure Kill_Switch and Graceful_Stop are callable from any branch and don’t break others.
> 
> 8) Tests: Wiring, Guards, and Regressions
> 
> Add/extend tests:
> 
> tests/wiring/test_import_graph.py (no cycles; orphans flagged)
> 
> tests/wiring/test_interface_conformance.py (ABCs implemented)
> 
> tests/wiring/test_data_registry.py (all modules resolve paths only via registry)
> 
> tests/modes/test_mode_guard.py (paper blocks live orders)
> 
> tests/modes/test_kill_switch.py (no new orders; positions managed)
> 
> tests/logs/test_logging_unified.py (no print; JSON structure)
> 
> Output a coverage summary; target ≥80% for wiring/guards.
> 
> 9) CI & Linting
> 
> Add a GitHub Action:
> 
> ruff + black + mypy + tests on 3.10/3.11.
> 
> Cache deps; artifact upload of artifacts/* on PRs.
> 
> Fail PR if: new orphan, new hard-coded path, interface broken, or mode guard bypass.
> 
> 10) Deliverables
> 
> artifacts/ folder with:
> 
> module_map.json, dependency_graph.png
> 
> interface_conformance.md
> 
> schema_report.md
> 
> path_replacements.md
> 
> deprecations.md
> 
> Refactor PR with:
> 
> Centralized imports to config.py + Data_Registry.py
> 
> Replaced prints → logger
> 
> ABC interfaces + adapters wired
> 
> Tests & CI added
> 
> Helper scripts to generate (place in tools/)
> 
> tools/Build_Dependency_Graph.py — parse AST/imports, produce module_map.json + dependency_graph.dot/png.
> 
> tools/Find_Hardcoded_Paths.py — regex scan for C:\\|/Users/|/mnt/|backup_data|.csv etc., suggest registry replacements.
> 
> tools/Check_Interface_Conformance.py — import implementations, verify ABCs, print missing methods.
> 
> tools/Check_Schemas.py — sample datasets, validate columns/dtypes/timezones.
> 
> tools/Replace_Print_With_Logger.py — safe auto-fix for print() → logger.info/debug.
> 
> Acceptance Criteria
> 
> No orphans or dead ends; dependency graph clean; cycles documented or removed.
> 
> All modules use Data_Registry & config.py (no stray paths/config).
> 
> Interfaces enforced; implementations pass conformance.
> 
> Unified logging; zero print() outside tests.
> 
> Guards prevent cross-wallet transfers and live orders in paper.
> 
> Tests + CI green; artifacts generated on PR.
> 
> Notes for the agent
> 
> Keep my module naming style (concise, consistent).
> 
> Don’t remove experimental code; if unused, mark as deprecated with reason & move to legacy/ (kept out of import path).
> 
> Be surgical and output a clear report so I can approve each change.
> 
> (Optional) Tiny starter commands (agent can run)
> 
> Generate graph & artifacts:
> 
> python tools/Build_Dependency_Graph.py
> 
> python tools/Find_Hardcoded_Paths.py
> 
> python tools/Check_Interface_Conformance.py
> 
> python tools/Check_Schemas.py

issue.title: Advice on collectstatic in build stage
issue.body:
So I'd be glad to have your help here with an issue but maybe also something to reconsider for this project.

Basically I'm deploying to Railway which injects ENV vars in the build stage of the Dockerfile only if they're specified as `ARG`.

I have an app that requires ENV vars that shouldn't have a default value (for example: fail loudly if we don't have `EMAIL_TOKEN`). Those are defined in my settings module.

You can see where I'm going with this. If I want to use this template on Railway I have two choices:

1. Move `collectstatic` out of the Dockerfile (will this have negative consequences? What do I do in development mode?)

2. Always define defaults for ENV vars. Passing each required ENV var as ARG to Dockerfile is not realistic, there are too many. Even if I was willing to pass secrets as ARGs (and I'm not)

Can collectstatic be moved out of Dockerfile somehow, without negative consequences?

issue.title: Support  "No category" for watched channels -> categories restrictions
issue.body:
### Expected Behavior

Stream can have no category selected, it would nice to be able to select this as custom "No category" option (or another name) in the GUI without crashes

### Current Behavior

Currently you can set "" as a category to restrict by using API, but in the GUI if you press on "Load Categories" it crashes with error.

`Uncaught TypeError: can't access property "trim", e is undefined`

### Possible Solution

Custom hardcoded selection with empty string "" for category name and id. From tests empty string worked for me, but should be double checked.

comment.body: I wasn't able to test with an actual stream as I didn't find any without a category but I tested the inverse which works. Let me know if this doesn't work.
